rd, Perthshire, Scotland","Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland":"Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Oliphant","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (London) and Scottish (Fife): from Old French <i>olifard</i> or <i>olifant</i>, of uncertain meaning. It has been suggested that this might be a derivative of Old French <i>olif</i> ‘olive’ + the pejorative suffix <i>-ard</i> ‘derisive nickname for one who preferred an olive branch to more martial weapons’; it may have denoted a man twisted like an olive-tree. The variant <i>Olifant</i> may have resulted from the substitution in Old Norman French of the sequence <i>l-r</i> by <i>l-n</i>, leading to a false association with Old French <i>olifant</i> ‘elephant’. This heraldic beast appears in the Scottish family's coats of arms. Branches of the Anglo-Norman family owned lands in both England and Scotland. The surname is now chiefly Scottish.","English: possibly a topographic name from residence at an inn known as the <i>Olyphaunt</i> or ‘elephant’, though whether this gave rise to a hereditary surname is unknown."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Oliphant was born in 1350, in Aberdalgie, Perthshire, Scotland, his father, Sir Walter Oliphant, was 16 and his mother, Mary Erskine, was 15. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Filla Brothwick. He died in 1417, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1350–1417":"1350–1417","1354–Male":"1354–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1376–1412":"1376–1412","–Male":"Surnud","1335–1411":"1335–1411","1